findings.code_snippet:
export interface TriggerResult {
  triggered: boolean
  triggerId: string
  triggerName: string
}

findings.suggestion:
Refactor to discriminated union:

type TriggerResult =
  | { triggered: true; triggerId: string; triggerName: string }
  | { triggered: false }

Update NOT_TRIGGERED to `{ triggered: false } as const` and update consumers to narrow via `if (trigger.triggered)` (already the case).

Introduce branded types for temporal values:

type UnixTimestampMs = number & { readonly __brand: 'UnixTimestampMs' }
type DurationMs = number & { readonly __brand: 'DurationMs' }

Apply to timestamp fields (UnixTimestampMs) and duration fields (DurationMs). Add constructor functions: `function toTimestamp(ms: number): UnixTimestampMs` with optional validation.

findings.code_snippet:
export interface TriggerCondition {
  id: string
  name: string
  check: (input: TriggerInput) => boolean
  cooldownMs: number
}

findings.suggestion:
Introduce branded types:

type TriggerId = string & { readonly __brand: 'TriggerId' }
type TriggerName = string & { readonly __brand: 'TriggerName' }

Use TriggerId for TriggerCondition.id, TriggerResult.triggerId, ProactiveResponse.triggerId, and Record<TriggerId, number> for lastTriggerTimes.

When implementing beyond the walking skeleton, make VectorStore generic:

interface VectorStore<M extends Record<string, unknown> = Record<string, unknown>> {
  store(embedding: number[], metadata: M): Promise<string>
  search(query: number[], topK: number): Promise<Array<{ id: string, score: number, metadata: M }>>
}
